 private realm and men to a public one. A third dimension—the social sphere—also existed and was a critical meeting ground for both genders. In the social worlds of love, livelihood, gossip, friendship, and mutual assistance, working people crossed ideological gender boundaries.The book's rare collection of original writings reinforces Hansen's arguments and also provides an intimate glimpse into antebellum New England life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aWomenzNew EnglandxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aanecdotal.  aantebellum new england life.  aautobiographies.  ablack and white.  achallenges conventional notions of gender roles.  adiaries.  ahalf century before civil war.  ahistorical research and sociological interpretation.  aletters.  amen and women.  amen to public realm.  anarrative of new englands working class.  awomen to private realm.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020561140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520917958?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520917958423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520917958/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY